				<h4 class="blogtxt">Effect of Stereotyping on Gender Diversity in Tech</h4>
				&#8212 February 12, 2015
				<br><br>
				
				University of Washington research published yesterday shows that inaccurate stereotypes are a key cause of gender disparity in both Engineering or Computer Science. 
				
				The study indicated that stereotypes depicting computer scientists and engineers as "geeky, brilliant and socially awkward males" contributes to lack of representation by women, and that, "broadening those stereotypes is key to attracting more girls to the two fields." You can  <a href="http://www.washington.edu/news/2015/02/11/how-to-interest-girls-in-computer-science-and-engineering-shift-the-stereotypes/" target="_blank">read their article here</a>.<br><br>
				 Coincidentally, late last year, CEO Melissa Liu wrote a LinkedIn piece about stereotypes and how they affect the expectations of adults of kids in their lives. Those expectations influence how adults in kids' lives encourage (or do not encourage) those kids towards engineering and programming activities. You can read that article <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/20141028212558-3330894-how-do-you-recognize-a-future-engineer" target="_blank">here</a>. <br><br>In a similar vein, there was a TEDx talk at the College of William and Mary last year where the speaker, Karen Catlin, talked about the fact that gender disparity in technology starts early in childhood. The example she gave was programming camps with 7-year-olds that were dominated by boys with very few girls. The point she made was that, at that age, it was the <i>parents</i> making the decisions as to what camps their kids would attend, and they were overwhelmingly sending their sons, and not their daughters, to computer camps. You can view that TEDx talk <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8uiEHaDSfgI" target="_blank">here</a>.
				
