				<h4 class="blogtxt">Tech Diversity Data and Exciting 2025 Labs News!</h4>
				&#8212 September 15, 2014
				<br><br>
				
				Some well-known tech companies have recently released diversity statistics, with surprising results. In case you missed the news, companies like Google, LinkedIn, Twitter, and Facebook have disclosed the demographics of their companies, their technology workers, and their leadership, based on both gender and race/ethnic background.<br><br>

				I have an engineering degree. I know what engineering demographics look like. And yet, the data surprised me… Why? <br><br>
				
				I’ve been around enough to understand that engineering is likely to be highly male… But for the <i>entire company</i> to be around <b>70% male</b> (Twitter, Google, Facebook) is hard to fathom. It’s surprising that there are not more women in other roles, such as Marketing, Sales, or Business Development. I have met so many capable women in those functions – there shouldn’t be a shortage of them, as there is in Engineering.<br><br>
				
				I applaud these companies for releasing the data. It’s hard to solve a problem you haven’t measured. “If you don’t measure it, you can’t improve it” as the saying goes. Hopefully, publicizing this data will help the companies drive change in their organizations. I look forward to seeing improvements in these measures over time.<br><br>

				Speaking of doing something about diversity… Let’s talk about some 2025 Labs news!<br><br>
				
