				<h4 class="blogtxt">College Mentoring in the News</h4>
				&#8212 April 22, 2014
				<br><br>
				Hot off the (electronic news) press is an article about our recent kick-off of a pilot mentoring program between USCS School of Engineering alumni and MESA Engineering undergraduates. It's a great article, and you can find it <a href="http://news.ucsc.edu/2014/04/alumni-mentors.html" target="_blank"> here</a>.<br><br>
					
				Interestingly enough, this morning's NPR Morning Edition highlighted <a href="http://www.npr.org/2014/04/22/305814367/evidence-of-racial-gender-biases-found-in-faculty-mentoring" target="_blank">evidence of racial and gender bias in faculty mentoring</a>. In this study, researchers drafted an email communication requesting a meeting, purportedly from a student, and emailed the request to 6500+ college professors at the top 250 colleges in the US. They used the same verbiage in each request, varying only the names. The names were chosen to provide a subtle hint to faculty of the requestor's gender, race, or ethnicity, and included a variety of ethnic-sounding names, such as Hispanic, Chinese, Indian, and African-American. 
				<br><br>Among the findings of the research: <p>
				<li>College professors are less likely to respond to requests for guidance from requestors with woman- or minority-sounding names </li><p>
				<li>Of those women or minority names who did get a response, the responses were less likely to be positive (that is, an agreement to meet) as compared to requester names that sounded like 'white male' names</li><p>
				<li>The researchers were surprised to find a significant amount of bias against Asian- and Indian-sounding names. Those ethnic groups are not traditionally underrepresented. However, the study showed quite measurable bias against them</li><p>
				<li>The Humanities showed the smallest difference between 'white male' names compared to woman- or minority-sounding names.</li></p>
				<li>The sciences showed more bias as compared to the Humanities</li><p>
				<li>Business academic departments showed the greatest amount - a 25% gap in positive responses between 'white, male' sounding names as opposed to female- or minority-sounding names</li><p>
				
				<p>We aren't always surprised to hear about gaps between white and traditionally-underrepresented ethnic groups, but is the bias against Asian- and Indian-sounding names surprising? What do you think? Send us an <a href="mailto:info@2025labs.com?Subject=Opinion%20on%20April%20Blog" target="_top">email</a> and let us know.
